#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:2
msgid "Release Schedule"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:5
msgid "Frequency"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:6
msgid ""
"New ROS 2 releases are produced every **every 12 months**. The rationale is "
"that a shorter cycle (like 6 months) results in significant overhead and "
"potentially many active releases at the same time (assuming they have the "
"same support length). On the other hand a longer cycle (like 2 years) is too "
"long for users to wait for new features to be available in a ROS 2 release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:11
msgid "Targeted Platforms"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:13
msgid ""
"Since non-LTS (long term support) Ubuntu releases are only supported for 9 "
"months, ROS 2 will not target those non-LTS Ubuntu releases. A single ROS 2 "
"distribution will only have full Tier 1 support for a **single** Ubuntu LTS. "
"The rationale is that fully supporting two Ubuntu LTS versions is a "
"tremendous overhead for our maintainers as there may be upstream "
"dependencies that differ by up to two years . On a case-by-case basis, a ROS "
"2 distribution may support an older Ubuntu LTS distribution as a Tier 3, "
"community-supported platform."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:18
msgid ""
"Since both macOS (or at least brew) and Windows are rolling platforms, we "
"aim to support the latest version available at the time of a ROS 2 "
"distribution's release. For Debian we also aim to target the latest stable "
"version; however, if that version is two years behind the Ubuntu version "
"then it might not be possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:22
msgid "Support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:25
msgid "LTS releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:27
msgid ""
"Since Ubuntu LTS releases come with **5 years** of standard support, we aim "
"for each ROS LTS distribution to have a similar support lifetime. In even "
"years new ROS 2 releases will happen one month after the Ubuntu LTS has been "
"released (which usually means a ROS 2 release in May). The ROS 2 release "
"will be supported until the end of the standard support window of the Ubuntu "
"LTS release, which is 4 years and 11 months from the ROS 2 release date."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:32
msgid "Non-LTS Releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:34
msgid ""
"In order to provide frequent releases to the community, in odd years a non-"
"LTS ROS 2 release will be published. It will always target the same Ubuntu "
"LTS as the previous ROS 2 LTS release but will only be supported for **1.5 "
"years**. This duration ensures that the non-LTS will overlap with the next "
"ROS LTS release by 6 months to provide a long enough transition window."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:39
msgid "Releases and support duration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:41
msgid "May 2021: G Turtle: non-LTS release, supported for 1.5 years"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:42
msgid "May 2022: H Turtle: LTS release, supported for 5 years"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:43
msgid "May 2023: I Turtle: non-LTS release, supported for 1.5 years"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:44
msgid "May 2024: J Turtle: LTS release, supported for 5 years"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/The-ROS2-Project/Release-Schedule.rst:45
msgid "and so on, alternating annually between LTS and non-LTS releases"
msgstr ""
